          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Trypanosomiasis</span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 20534,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Toxoplasmosis</span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 20535,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Piroplasmosis</span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 20536,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Leishmaniasis</span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 7-year-old boy living in a rural area of India presents with unilateral eyelid swelling, conjunctivitis, and fever. He has no significant past medical history. His family reports an increase in insects in their home, especially at night. Physical examination reveals unilateral periorbital swelling.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/05/picture9.jpg\" style=\"height:201px; width:300px\" /></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">This condition is associated most commonly with which organism?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5100239",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 35610,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans.</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>A. Trypanosomiasis</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Romana sign</strong>, characterized by <strong>unilateral periorbital swelling </strong>and <strong>conjunctivitis</strong>, is a <strong>classic sign of acute Chagas disease</strong>, which is caused by the <strong>protozoan parasite Trypanosoma cruzi</strong>. Though not endemic to India, cases can be seen in individuals with a travel history to endemic areas in Latin America.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Life cycle</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/05/picture10.jpg\" style=\"height:408px; width:600px\" /></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B)</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<strong>Toxoplasmosis </strong>does <strong>not typically present with Romana sign.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C)</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<strong>Piroplasmosis</strong>, caused by <strong>Babesia species</strong>, presents with fever and hemolytic anemia but not with Romana sign.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D)</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<strong>Leishmaniasis </strong>can cause <strong>cutaneous or visceral symptoms</strong>, but Romana sign is not a feature.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Trypanosomiasis</strong>. <strong>Romana sign</strong>, marked by <strong>unilateral periorbital swelling </strong>and <strong>conjunctivitis</strong>, indicates <strong>acute Chagas disease from Trypanosoma cruzi</strong>. It&#39;s <strong>rare in India </strong>but seen in those who&#39;ve visited endemic Latin American regions.&nbsp;</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Toxoplasmosis, Piroplasmosis </strong>(Babesia species), and <strong>Leishmaniasis don&#39;t exhibit Romana sign</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><u>Ref</u>: Apurba Sastry&rsquo;s Essentials of Medical Parasitology/p82, 2e/p64.</span></span></span></span></strong></p>",
